onal accounts of the onset of peace, grounded in ‘mutually hurting stalemate’ and ‘ripeness’, which downgrade the political and economic aspects of conflict. Military stalemate had been evident since the early 1970s and offers little in explaining the timing of the peace process. Moreover, republicans and loyalists based their ceasefires upon very different perceptions of transformation or victory.Based on a Leverhulme Trust project and written by an expert team, Abandoning Conflict offers a new analysis, based on subtle interplays of military, political, economic and personal changes and experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEx-convictsxPolitical activityzNorthern Ireland. 0aEx-convictszNorthern IrelandxAttitudes. 0aPeace-buildingzNorthern Ireland. 0aPolitical prisonerszNorthern IrelandxAttitudes. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh  aNorthern Ireland.  aarmed groups.  aceasefires.  aconflict.  aformer prisoners.  aloyalists.  apeace process.  apeace.  arepublicans.  aviolence.1 aMcAuley, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcAuley, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGlynn, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShirlow, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTonge, Jon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTonge, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779343040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793430423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793430/ori